                        <p style="color: #800000; font-family: Tahoma; font-size: 23px;">By Vincent Mogaka Muturi.   22nd/05/2025</p>
                        <p style="color: black; font-family: 'Tahoma'; font-size: 20px;">
                            🚶 Walking constitutes the primary mode of transport for the majority of the African population, accounting for approximately 78% of all trips relative to other modes.<br />
                            <br />
                            Despite this, urban infrastructure development in Nairobi continues to heavily prioritize 🚗 motorized transport, with minimal consideration for alternative modes such as 🚲 cycling.<br />
                            <br />
                            The increasing demand for knowledge and investment in urban cycling highlights the limitations of motorized transport systems—manifested in persistent traffic congestion, overcrowded parking facilities, elevated air pollution levels, and a high incidence of road traffic accidents. These challenges, however, also present a critical opportunity to reimagine and invest in active mobility solutions.<br />
                            <br />
                            This research seeks to promote the integration of Non-Motorized Transport (NMT)—specifically walking and cycling—as a strategic approach to mitigating traffic congestion in South B Estate. Through detailed analysis of empirical data, the research puts forward practical recommendations to position active mobility as a sustainable and effective response to Nairobi’s urban transport challenges.
                        </p>
